    "34173213": {
      "title": "Density gradient ultracentrifugation of serum lipoproteins in a swinging bucket rotor",
      "abstract": "Publisher Summary This chapter describes the density gradient method and presents examples of its application for the separation of human and baboon serum lipoproteins. The results indicate that some difficulties may be encountered using density gradient centrifugation for studies of serum from hypertriglyceridimic subjects, for example, serum samples, which have elevated triglycerides that can form a cake at the top of the tube that hinders elution of the contents of the centrifuge tube. Therefore, the method is not appropriate for the screening of large populations because only six samples can be run at a time. However, a major advantage of the density gradient procedure is its sensitivity, and another important feature is that it provides a visual display of the continuous lipoprotein distribution. The chapter thus suggests that fractionation of serum lipoproteins into a continuous lipoprotein profile as contrasted with discrete density classes gives a more informative picture of the densities and heterogeneity of the lipoprotein species and the appearance of minor or new lipoprotein species."
    }
  },
